        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Since the expected velocity width of the [CII]157 emission is broad (~1500 km/s), we observe the [CII] emisison line by using two basebands (Baseband-1 and Baseband-2) with the lowest resolution (v_res = 19.395 km/s with the widest coverage of 1875 MHz) mode. This setup results in the frequency coverage from 480.51 GHz to 483.98 GHz (that corresponds to the velocity width of ~2200 km/s). The remaining two bassbands are used to detect the continuum emission. Since a wide-coverage setting is preferred for detecting the continuum emission, we select the widest coverage mode for the these continuum bands as well.

For reducing the datarate of this science goal, we adopt 8 channel binning in Baseband-1 and Baseband-2 (for [CII]) and 16 channel binning for the remaining basebands for continuum. This velocity binning does not affect our science goal, as the resulting velocity resolution (2.4 km/s) is much finer than any velocity structure expected for our target.
The data rate for this setting is ~2.3 MB/s which is moderately low. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>For our science goal, we do not need to resolve the internal structure for each component. The required angular resolution is therefore set to 1.0 arcsec.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The primary purpose of this Science Goal is to detect the [CII] emission (rest-frame wavelength and frequency 157.741 micron and 1900.537 GHz) in the galaxy COSMOS XID147 at z_opt = 2.941. For this redshift, the observed-frame wavelength and frequency are 621.657 micron and 482.247 GHz, respectively. This corresponds to a frequency where the atmospheric transmission is relatively good in the Band 8. For the expected large velocity width, we use two basebands to cover the whole line profile.

Thanks to the deep multi-wavelength observations available for COSMOS, the SED of this source is well determined through the Subaru, Spitzer, and Herschel data. The FIR luminosity inferred from the SED fitting is 3 x 10^46 erg/s. We assume the luminosity ratio of log (L[CII]/L_FIR) = -3.5 rather conservatively as a high-redshift source based on recent reports (e.g., Maiolino et al. 2009, A&amp;A, 500, L1; Swinbank et al. 2012, MN, 427, 1066). Then we obtain the expected [CII] luminoisity of L[CII] = 1 x 10^43 erg/s, which leads to F_[CII] = 1.3 x 10^-16 erg/s/cm^2 that corresponds to 5.4 mJy by assuming the velocity width of 1500 km/s. In order to detect this [CII]157 emission with S/N = 10, the required sensitivity is 0.54 mJy (rms). </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
